Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgxPb8TG9rQsglFi4KN4AaABAg,,@randybass8842,"Rick was traumatized by Ilsa not showing up at the train in Paris with no explanation, and hated his memories of that time. Even when Ilsa came into the bar after closing, he did not expect to hear an acceptable reason as to why she left him and insulted her. But when she came to his apartment, she was able to give him an acceptable reason that he could accept that her love for him was genuine at the time and still was. What that did was restore the true love that Rick also had for her and made his memories of Paris a happy time again. So, in the end, when he says, ""We'll always have Paris,"" that shows that he has been able to drop the caustic personality that he had. It restored in him that he had once had true love and lost it through no fault of his or of Ilsa. So it was not necessary to cling to that love,  and he could let her go for the greater good of the war effort.",2026-05-05T04:59:12Z,2026-05-05T04:59:12Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-19T02:01:09.277940
Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgxTK5Xtp6zATjg4z2F4AaABAg,,@keithmartin4670,"The scene where they try to out sing each other is truly great if you know the context.  The Nazis start singing “Die Wacht am Rhein”, a German patriotic song.  The others respond with “La Marseillaise”, the national anthem of France.  Add to that the fact that many of the actors and extras were refugees from the Nazis in real life, and it’s a truly wonderful moment.",2026-05-05T02:03:17Z,2026-05-05T02:03:17Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-19T02:01:09.277943
