AFCON,J88JypA1AM8,Ugxhq6LPltkzy8wRRVB4AaABAg,,@ParmaNaik-f3m,"When high-profile pundits like Jamie Carragher frame this incident as ""this wouldn't happen in Europe,"" it's not just a comparison of sporting bodies; it taps into a much deeper and more damaging well of condescension.

Here’s why that kind of rhetoric is so problematic, even if it's not intentionally malicious:

· The ""Civilizing"" Narrative: This kind of statement feeds into the tired colonial stereotype that Africa is a place of chaos and incompetence, needing the order and structure that Europe provides. It ignores that European football has its own sordid history of corruption (FIFA's ""Blatter-era"" scandals, UEFA's own governance issues) and fan violence. The assumption is that Europe is the ""adult"" and Africa is the ""child"" who can't manage its own affairs.
· Ignoring the Root Cause: By reducing the issue to a simplistic ""African incompetence"" argument, it ignores the real context. The delay in the ruling wasn't just ""chaos""; it was a political and bureaucratic failure. More importantly, it completely absolves the actual actors on the pitch—the Senegalese players who walked off—of their role in creating the initial problem.
· Undertones of Superiority: The phrase ""smacks of undertones"" is perfect because it captures the subtle, implied message. It's not an overtly racist statement, but it carries the weight of a long history where Africa is constantly measured against a European standard and found wanting. It dismisses the possibility of an African institution making a fair, if delayed, judgement on its own merits.

It’s a classic case of ""damned if you do, damned if you don't."" If CAF had done nothing, they'd be accused of incompetence. They made a ruling (however late), and it's still used as evidence of dysfunction by those who view the continent through a prejudiced lens.

The reality is far messier: CAF made a legally defensible but procedurally disastrous decision. But pundits reaching for the ""in Europe"" trope are offering a veneer of objectivity that masks a very old and tired prejudice.",2026-03-19T13:35:42Z,2026-03-19T13:35:42Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-19T02:02:39.714534
